{# Entity + fact extraction prompt. Modules 2+3 of AtomicWritePipeline. #}
Extract a structured triple from this atomic fact. Identify the subject entity, predicate (relation type), and object entity.

## Atomic fact
{{ atomic_fact }}

## Predicates
Use one of these when applicable: {{ preferred_predicates | join(", ") }}.
If none fits, create a new ALL_CAPS predicate (e.g. GRADUATED_FROM).

## Output (JSON)
{
  "subject": {"name": "...", "entity_type": "person|organization|project|place|concept|tool"},
  "predicate": "WORKS_AT",
  "object": {"name": "...", "entity_type": "..."},
  "fact_text": "human-readable detail from the fact",
  "t_valid": 1234567890000 or null,
  "t_invalid": 1234567890000 or null
}

For temporal bounds: use unix milliseconds if the fact mentions specific times. Otherwise null.

## Examples

Fact: "Ivan works at Acme Corp as a senior engineer"
Output: {"subject": {"name": "Ivan", "entity_type": "person"}, "predicate": "WORKS_AT", "object": {"name": "Acme Corp", "entity_type": "organization"}, "fact_text": "Ivan works at Acme Corp as a senior engineer", "t_valid": null, "t_invalid": null}

Fact: "The project uses Python and Rust"
Output: {"subject": {"name": "The project", "entity_type": "project"}, "predicate": "USES_TECH", "object": {"name": "Python", "entity_type": "tool"}, "fact_text": "The project uses Python", "t_valid": null, "t_invalid": null}
(Note: extract one triple per fact; for "Python and Rust" use two separate extractions or pick primary)

Fact: "Maria prefers dark mode"
Output: {"subject": {"name": "Maria", "entity_type": "person"}, "predicate": "PREFERS", "object": {"name": "dark mode", "entity_type": "concept"}, "fact_text": "Maria prefers dark mode", "t_valid": null, "t_invalid": null}
